==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*juk-'', from Indo-European ''*i̯ugom''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[juc]] (Dutch [[juk]]), Old High German [[joh]] (German [[Joch]]), Old Norse [[ok]] (Swedish [[ok]]), Gothic [[𐌾𐌿𐌺]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Vedic Sanskrit [[युगम्]], Greek [[ζυγόν]], Latin [[iugum]], Old Church Slavonic [[иго]] (Polish [[igo]]), Lithuanian [[jungti|jùngti]], Welsh [[iau]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /jeok/

===Noun===
'''ġeoc''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''ġeocu''')
# a [[yoke]]

